This version of ed(1) is not strictly POSIX compliant, as described in
the POSIX 1003.2 document.  The following is a summary of the omissions,
extensions and possible deviations from POSIX 1003.2.

OMISSIONS
---------
1) Locale(3) is not supported yet.

2) For backwards compatibility, the POSIX rule that says a range of
   addresses cannot be used where only a single address is expected has
   been relaxed.

3) To support the BSD `s' command (see extension [1] below),
   substitution patterns cannot be delimited by numbers or the characters
   `r', `g' and `p'.  In contrast, POSIX specifies any character except
   space or newline can be used as a delimiter.

EXTENSIONS
----------
1) BSD commands have been implemented wherever they do not conflict with
   the POSIX standard.  The BSD-ism's included are:
	i) `s' (i.e., s[n][rgp]*) to repeat a previous substitution,
	ii) `W' for appending text to an existing file,
	iii) `wq' for exiting after a write,
	iv) `z' for scrolling through the buffer, and
	v) BSD line addressing syntax (i.e., `^' and `%') is recognized.

2) The POSIX interactive global commands `G' and `V' are extended to
   support multiple commands, including `a', `i' and `c'.  The command
   format is the same as for the global commands `g' and `v', i.e., one
   command per line with each line, except for the last, ending in a
   backslash (\).

3) An extension to the POSIX file commands `E', `e', `r', `W' and `w' is
   that <file> arguments are processed for backslash escapes, i.e.,  any
   character preceded by a backslash is interpreted literally.  If the
   first unescaped character of a <file> argument is a bang (!), then the
   rest of the line is interpreted as a shell command, and no escape
   processing is performed by ed.

4) Additional command-line flags have been added:
	-E  Use extended regular expressions (ERE) instead of basic (BRE).
	-P  Use PCRE2 regular expressions.  Mutually exclusive with -E.
	    Enables lookahead/lookbehind, named captures, \d shorthand,
	    and other PCRE2-specific syntax.  Only available when oed is
	    built with libpcre2-8.
	-l  Loose exit status: continue past ERR-level errors in scripts
	    instead of exiting with status 1.  Combined with -T, all commands
	    are attempted; the wet run commits only if every command succeeded.
	-v  Verbose mode: print an explanation for each `?' notification;
	    substitution commands also report the count of substitutions
	    made to standard error.
	-T  Transaction mode (dry-run/wet-run): all editing commands execute
	    in memory; `w' and `W' are deferred and do not touch disk.  Shell
	    escapes (`!cmd', `r !cmd', `e !cmd', `w !cmd') are forbidden.
	    On any error, in-memory changes are rolled back and the process
	    exits with status 1; no deferred writes fire.  On clean exit, all
	    deferred writes execute in order.  Combined with -l, all commands
	    are attempted and the wet run fires only if every command succeeded.
	-n  Always-number: enable persistent line numbering at startup,
	    equivalent to an immediate `N' command.
	-A  Success token: print `OK <dot>' after every successful command,
	    where <dot> is the current line number after the command.  For
	    example, a successful `p' on line 3 prints `OK 3'.  A
	    pipe-driving agent can detect command boundaries and track dot
	    on a single stream without a separate `=' round-trip.
	-M  Machine/agent mode: convenience flag that enables -s, -A, -v, -l, -E,
	    and -T simultaneously.  Does not imply -n.
	-R  Read-only mode: reject any command that modifies the buffer or
	    writes to a file (a, c, d, e, E, i, j, m, r, s, t, u, w, W, x,
	    and shell escapes).  Read and search commands continue to work.
	    Unlike GNU ed's -r (restricted mode), -R restricts buffer
	    modification rather than file-path access.
	-e cmd  Inline command: append cmd to the list of commands to execute
	    before reading standard input.  May be repeated.  Implies -s.
	Exit code scheme: ERR-level errors exit 1; EMOD (unsaved buffer) exits
	    2; clean exit is 0; internal panic is 3.  This aligns with GNU ed.

5) New commands have been added:
	`B' prints a one-line machine-readable buffer summary to standard
	   output: current-addr, total-lines, modified-flag, undo-depth, and
	   filename.  undo-depth is 1 if an undo is available, 0 otherwise.
	`N' toggles persistent line numbering: when active, all output lines
	   are prefixed with their line number and a tab.
	`y' yanks (copies) the addressed lines into a cut buffer.
	`x' puts (inserts) the cut buffer contents after the addressed line.

	`K' lists all currently set marks to standard output, one per line,
	   in the form `'\''x addr' (mark letter and line address).
	Named register prefix: preceding `y' or `x' with `"r' (where r is
	   a lower-case letter) stores or retrieves a named register instead
	   of the default unnamed cut buffer.  26 named registers (a-z) are
	   provided in addition to the default.

	`C' (addr1,addr2)C/re/ counts the lines in the addressed range
	   matching re and prints the integer count.  The current address is
	   unchanged.  Cannot be used inside a global command.
	`=' (addr1,addr2)= now prints both resolved addresses separated by a
	   space when a range is given; with a single address it prints that
	   address; with no address it prints addr_last (existing behaviour
	   preserved).
	`Z' (1,$)Z computes the Adler-32 checksum of the addressed lines and
	   prints it as eight lowercase hexadecimal digits.  Each line's bytes
	   are fed to the algorithm followed by a synthetic newline separator.
	   NUL bytes in binary files are hashed as stored.  On an empty buffer
	   the output is 00000001 without error.  The current address is
	   unchanged.
6) All `?' error tokens, byte counts from `r'/`w', and the `!' shell-
   escape prompt are written to standard output rather than standard
   error.  This allows scripts and automated tools to read a single
   stream without multiplexing descriptors.

DEVIATIONS
----------
1) Though ed is not a stream editor, it can be used to edit binary files.
   To assist in binary editing, when a file containing at least one ASCII
   NUL character is written, a newline is not appended if it did not
   already contain one upon reading.  In particular, reading /dev/null
   prior to writing prevents appending a newline to a binary file.

   For example, to create a file with ed containing a single NUL character:
      $ ed file
      a
      ^@
      .
      r /dev/null
      wq

    Similarly, to remove a newline from the end of binary `file':
      $ ed file
      r /dev/null
      wq

2) Since the behavior of `u' (undo) within a `g' (global) command list is
   not specified by POSIX, it follows the behavior of the SunOS ed:
   undo forces a global command list to be executed only once, rather than
   for each line matching a global pattern.  In addition, each instance of
   `u' within a global command undoes all previous commands (including
   undo's) in the command list.  This seems the best way, since the
   alternatives are either too complicated to implement or too confusing
   to use.

   The global/undo combination is useful for masking errors that
   would otherwise cause a script to fail.  For instance, an ed script
   to remove any occurrences of either `censor1' or `censor2' might be
   written as:
   	ed - file <<EOF
	1g/.*/u\
	,s/censor1//g\
	,s/censor2//g
	...

3) The `m' (move) command within a `g' command list also follows the SunOS
   ed implementation: any moved lines are removed from the global command's
   `active' list.

4) If ed is invoked with a name argument prefixed by a bang (!), then the
   remainder of the argument is interpreted as a shell command.  To invoke
   ed on a file whose name starts with bang, prefix the name with a
   backslash.
